---
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
---

<MainLayout
    title="Bass Tones"
    description="Step-by-step Ableton Live device chains for achieving gothic / post-punk bass tones — deep sub presence, mid-scooped distortion, and relentless percussive attack."
>
    <section class="content-intro">
        <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">Studio Workflow</p>
            <h1>Bass Tones</h1>
            <p class="content-intro__lede">
                Repeatable Ableton Live device chains for gothic / post-punk
                bass — deep sub presence, mid-scooped distortion, chorus-widened
                low-mids, and a relentless percussive attack. Set up once, save
                as a rack, and recall instantly on any project.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="content-intro__actions">
            <a href="/workflow/signal-chain" class="button-secondary"
                >Signal Chain</a
            >
        </div>
    </section>

    <article class="prose prose-invert">
        <h2>Gothic / Post-Punk</h2>
        <p>
            The gothic / post-punk bass sound (The Cure, Cocteau Twins, Siouxsie
            and the Banshees) is defined by deep sub presence, mid-scooped
            distortion, chorus-widened low-mids, and a driving percussive
            attack. The two setups below cover a real bass guitar through the
            MOTU and a fully MIDI-driven synthetic bass using Ableton's built-in
            Analog instrument.
        </p>

        <hr />

        <h3>Section A — Real Bass Guitar (through MOTU UltraLite Mk3)</h3>

        <h4>Step 1 — Hardware signal chain</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Bass guitar → MOTU UltraLite Mk3 <strong>Input 1 or 2</strong>
                (front combo jack)
            </li>
            <li>
                Enable <strong>Hi-Z / Instrument mode</strong> on that input in CueMix
                FX
            </li>
            <li>
                Gain staging target: peak <strong>−12 to −6 dBFS</strong> while playing
                hard
            </li>
            <li>
                Ableton audio track: <em>Audio From</em> → <code>Ext. In 1</code
                >
                (Mono)
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Step 2 — Ableton audio track setup</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Track name: <code>Bass – Gothic</code></li>
            <li>
                Monitor: <strong>In</strong> (or <strong>Auto</strong> when armed)
            </li>
            <li>
                No clip gain adjustments needed if gain-staged correctly at the
                MOTU
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Step 3 — Device chain</h4>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>#</th>
                    <th>Device</th>
                    <th>Key parameters</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>1</td>
                    <td><strong>Tuner</strong></td>
                    <td>Always first; mute output while tuning</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>2</td>
                    <td><strong>EQ Eight</strong> (pre-amp)</td>
                    <td>
                        High-pass at 40 Hz (steep, remove sub-rumble); boost +3
                        dB at 80–100 Hz (fundamental punch); cut −4 dB narrow
                        notch at 400–500 Hz (remove boxiness)
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>3</td>
                    <td><strong>Amp</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        Model: <code>Bass</code>; Drive: 55–65; Bass: 65; Mid:
                        35; Treble: 50; Presence: 45; Volume: 80; Blend: 100%
                        wet
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>4</td>
                    <td><strong>Cabinet</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        Cabinet: <code>1×15</code>; Microphone: <code
                            >Dynamic 421 Off Axis</code
                        >; Distance: 0.4 m; Mix: 100%
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>5</td>
                    <td><strong>Chorus-Ensemble</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        Mode: <code>Classic</code>; Rate: 0.3 Hz; Depth: 55%;
                        Delay: 2.0 ms; Feedback: 15%; Dry/Wet: 40% — widens the
                        bass mid-presence without muddying the low end
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>6</td>
                    <td><strong>Compressor</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        Threshold: −20 dBFS; Ratio: 3:1; Attack: 10 ms; Release:
                        150 ms; Makeup: +4 dB; Knee: Soft — tighten attack
                        transients while preserving note sustain
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>7</td>
                    <td><strong>EQ Eight</strong> (post-comp)</td>
                    <td>
                        Boost +2 dB shelf at 60 Hz (restore sub-bass body after
                        compression); cut −2 dB at 2–3 kHz (keep it dark)
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>8</td>
                    <td><strong>Reverb</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        Decay: 1.5–2.5 s; Pre-delay: 10 ms; Diffuse: 60%; Size:
                        70%; Dry/Wet: 20–25% — subtle room depth, not a wash
                    </td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4>Step 4 — Send / Return setup</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Add a dedicated Return track: <code>Return — Bass Space</code>
            </li>
            <li>
                Insert <strong>Reverb</strong> with Decay 3–4 s, Diffuse 70%, Size
                80%, Dry/Wet 100% (wet-only return)
            </li>
            <li>
                Send the Bass track to this return at <strong>−12 dB</strong>;
                blend to taste for genre-appropriate depth
            </li>
            <li>
                Keep the send subtle — gothic bass is present and grounded, not
                floating in reverb
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Step 5 — Save as Rack</h4>
        <ol>
            <li>
                Click <strong>EQ Eight (pre-amp)</strong> in the device chain, then
                <kbd>Shift</kbd>-click the final <strong>Reverb</strong>
                to select devices 2–8 — leave <strong>Tuner</strong> outside the rack
                so it remains accessible at the top of the chain
            </li>
            <li>
                Right-click the selection → <strong>Group</strong> — Ableton wraps
                them in an <strong>Audio Effect Rack</strong>
            </li>
            <li>
                Click the rack title bar and rename it
                <code>Bass – Gothic</code>
            </li>
            <li>
                Right-click the rack title bar → <strong
                    >Save to User Library</strong
                > — saves as a <code>.adg</code> preset under
                <em>Places → User Library</em> in the browser; drag onto any future
                audio track to recall the full processing chain
            </li>
            <li>
                Note: the <code>Return — Bass Space</code> track is not stored in
                the rack — save the entire Live Set as a template to preserve the
                return routing alongside the rack
            </li>
        </ol>

        <hr />

        <h3>Section B — MIDI Bass (no real instrument required)</h3>
        <p>
            Use this setup to compose gothic bass lines without a physical bass
            guitar. Ableton's <strong>Analog</strong> instrument models the characteristic
            dark, slightly overdriven synth-bass tone used across many post-punk records.
        </p>

        <h4>Step 1 — Track setup</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Create a new <strong>MIDI track</strong> in Ableton</li>
            <li>Track name: <code>Bass – Gothic (Synth)</code></li>
            <li>
                Load <strong>Analog</strong> as the instrument
            </li>
            <li>
                MIDI input: any keyboard controller (Launchkey 37, P-225, or
                Push 1 in Note Mode)
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Step 2 — Analog instrument settings</h4>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Parameter</th>
                    <th>Value</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>OSC 1</td>
                    <td>Sawtooth, Octave −1</td>
                    <td
                        >Foundation tone; detuned slightly flat (−5 ct) for
                        weight</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>OSC 2</td>
                    <td>Square wave, Octave −1, −10 ct detune</td>
                    <td>Adds meat; detuning creates slight movement</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Filter type</td>
                    <td>Low-pass 24 dB</td>
                    <td>Steep cutoff for dark character</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Cutoff</td>
                    <td>300–450 Hz</td>
                    <td>Dark and mid-scooped; high harmonics roll off</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Resonance</td>
                    <td>20–30%</td>
                    <td>Slight emphasis without whistling</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Filter Env (Attack)</td>
                    <td>5 ms</td>
                    <td>Nearly instant — percussive pluck</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Filter Env (Decay)</td>
                    <td>120 ms</td>
                    <td>Short decay gives the signature "thwack"</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Filter Env (Amount)</td>
                    <td>+25%</td>
                    <td>Briefly opens filter on each hit, then closes</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Amp Env (Attack)</td>
                    <td>8 ms</td>
                    <td>Slight softening of initial transient</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Amp Env (Decay)</td>
                    <td>300 ms</td>
                    <td>Sustains for driving eighth-note patterns</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Amp Env (Sustain)</td>
                    <td>70%</td>
                    <td>Hold level for tied / held notes</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>LFO (optional)</td>
                    <td>Sine, 0.5 Hz, routed to Cutoff at +10%</td>
                    <td>Very slow filter movement for extended passages</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Glide</td>
                    <td>20–40 ms</td>
                    <td
                        >Connects notes — characteristic post-punk bass slides</td
                    >
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4>Step 3 — Device chain after Analog</h4>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>#</th>
                    <th>Device</th>
                    <th>Parameters</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>1</td>
                    <td><strong>Saturator</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        Drive: 30–40%; Shape: <code>Soft Sine</code>; Dry/Wet:
                        70% — adds harmonic grit without harsh clipping
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>2</td>
                    <td><strong>EQ Eight</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        HP at 40 Hz; boost +3 dB at 80 Hz; cut −3 dB at 400 Hz;
                        cut −2 dB at 2.5 kHz
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>3</td>
                    <td><strong>Chorus-Ensemble</strong></td>
                    <td
                        >Same as Section A — Rate 0.3 Hz, Depth 55%, Dry/Wet 40%</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>4</td>
                    <td><strong>Compressor</strong></td>
                    <td>
                        Threshold: −18 dBFS; Ratio: 3:1; Attack: 8 ms; Release:
                        120 ms; Makeup: +3 dB
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>5</td>
                    <td><strong>Reverb</strong></td>
                    <td>Decay 1.5 s; Pre-delay 8 ms; Dry/Wet 20%</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4>Step 4 — MIDI tips for gothic / post-punk feel</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Use <strong>driving eighth-note patterns</strong> locked tight to
                the kick drum — this defines the propulsive post-punk rhythmic feel
            </li>
            <li>
                Play primarily in the <strong>E1–A2</strong> range; drop to
                <strong>B0 or low E0</strong> for climactic sections
            </li>
            <li>
                Use <strong>staccato notes</strong> (50–60% note length) to let each
                attack punch through; avoid legato unless sliding
            </li>
            <li>
                Apply <strong>Velocity automation</strong> to build intensity across
                8- or 16-bar sections — start around 85, build to 110–120
            </li>
            <li>
                Double the bass line with a second instance detuned
                <strong>+12 cents</strong> and blended at −6 dB for sub-width without
                muddiness
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Step 5 — Save as Rack</h4>
        <ol>
            <li>
                Click <strong>Analog</strong> in the device chain, then
                <kbd>Shift</kbd>-click the final <strong>Reverb</strong> to select
                the instrument and all downstream effects
            </li>
            <li>
                Right-click the selection → <strong>Group</strong> — Ableton wraps
                them in an <strong>Instrument Rack</strong>
            </li>
            <li>
                Click the rack title bar and rename it
                <code>Bass – Gothic (Synth)</code>
            </li>
            <li>
                Right-click the rack title bar → <strong
                    >Save to User Library</strong
                > — saves under <em>Places → User Library</em>
                as a <code>.adg</code> preset; drag onto any new MIDI track to recall
                the full Analog + processing chain in one step
            </li>
        </ol>

        <hr />

        <h3>
            Section C — Teletone Retrograde Bass (no real instrument required)
        </h3>
        <p>
            Use this setup to compose gothic bass lines with sampled bass guitar
            articulations. <strong>Teletone Audio Retrograde Bass</strong> provides
            modelled electric bass fingering and picking styles driven by MIDI from
            any controller — Launchkey 37, P-225, or Push 1 in Note Mode. It gives
            the organic attack and string dynamics of a real bass without the hardware,
            making it the closest MIDI alternative to Section A.
        </p>

        <h4>Step 1 — Track setup</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Create a new <strong>MIDI track</strong> in Ableton</li>
            <li>Track name: <code>Retrograde – Gothic</code></li>
            <li>
                Load <strong>Teletone Audio Retrograde Bass</strong> as the instrument
            </li>
            <li>MIDI input: Launchkey 37 Mk3, P-225, or Push 1</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Step 2 — Retrograde Bass plugin settings</h4>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Parameter</th>
                    <th>Value</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Pickup</td>
                    <td>Neck (or Neck+Bridge blend, neck-heavy)</td>
                    <td
                        >Warmer, darker fundamental — avoid bridge-only for this
                        genre</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Playing style</td>
                    <td>Fingered</td>
                    <td
                        >Rounder attack than pick; the slight pluck softness
                        suits post-punk</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Tone knob</td>
                    <td>35–45%</td>
                    <td>Roll off top end — keep it dark and mid-forward</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Volume / Output</td>
                    <td>70–75%</td>
                    <td>Leave headroom for the downstream amp and compressor</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Noise / ambience</td>
                    <td>On, −20 dB</td>
                    <td
                        >Adds organic string noise; keep it subtle so it sits
                        under the distortion</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Velocity response</td>
                    <td>Linear</td>
                    <td
                        >Consistent attack across the driving eighth-note
                        pattern</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Articulation</td>
                    <td>Standard / legato slides for transitions</td>
                    <td
                        >Use MIDI note overlap to trigger slides between root
                        notes</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Tuning</td>
                    <td>Standard or Drop D</td>
                    <td
                        >Drop D extends the low range to D1 for heavier passages</td
                    >
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4>Step 3 — Device chain after Retrograde Bass</h4>
        <p>
            Apply the same processing as Section A (skip the Tuner — not needed
            for MIDI):
        </p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>#</th>
                    <th>Device</th>
                    <th>Parameters</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>1</td>
                    <td><strong>EQ Eight</strong> (pre-amp)</td>
                    <td
                        >HP at 40 Hz; boost +3 dB at 80–100 Hz; cut −4 dB narrow
                        notch at 400–500 Hz</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>2</td>
                    <td><strong>Amp</strong></td>
                    <td
                        >Model: <code>Bass</code>; Drive: 55–65; Bass: 65; Mid:
                        35; Treble: 50; Presence: 45; Volume: 80; Blend: 100%
                        wet</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>3</td>
                    <td><strong>Cabinet</strong></td>
                    <td
                        ><code>1×15</code>; Dynamic 421 Off Axis; Distance: 0.4
                        m; Mix: 100%</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>4</td>
                    <td><strong>Chorus-Ensemble</strong></td>
                    <td
                        >Same as Section A — Mode: Classic; Rate: 0.3 Hz; Depth:
                        55%; Dry/Wet: 40%</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>5</td>
                    <td><strong>Compressor</strong></td>
                    <td
                        >Threshold: −20 dBFS; Ratio: 3:1; Attack: 10 ms;
                        Release: 150 ms; Makeup: +4 dB; Knee: Soft</td
                    >
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>6</td>
                    <td><strong>EQ Eight</strong> (post-comp)</td>
                    <td>Boost +2 dB shelf at 60 Hz; cut −2 dB at 2–3 kHz</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>7</td>
                    <td><strong>Reverb</strong></td>
                    <td
                        >Decay: 1.5–2.5 s; Pre-delay: 10 ms; Diffuse: 60%; Size:
                        70%; Dry/Wet: 20–25%</td
                    >
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
            Add the same <code>Return — Bass Space</code> return track from Section
            A and send <code>Retrograde – Gothic</code> to it at −12 dB.
        </p>

        <h4>Step 4 — MIDI tips for Retrograde Bass</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Use <strong>overlapping MIDI notes</strong> (legato input) on step
                changes to trigger Retrograde's slide articulation — this replicates
                the gliding position shifts common in post-punk bass playing
            </li>
            <li>
                Keep notes in the <strong>E1–A2</strong> range for the main groove;
                Retrograde's fingered samples are most natural in this register
            </li>
            <li>
                Set note lengths to <strong>55–65%</strong> of the grid division for
                staccato attack; increase to 90% on held root notes under chord changes
            </li>
            <li>
                Use <strong>Velocity between 80 and 105</strong> — avoid very low
                or very high velocities to keep the sampled dynamics feeling even
                across the groove
            </li>
            <li>
                For a thicker sound, duplicate the track, transpose the copy
                <strong>−12 semitones</strong> (one octave down) and blend it at −9
                dB beneath the main track to reinforce sub fundamentals
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Step 5 — Save as Rack</h4>
        <ol>
            <li>
                Click <strong>Retrograde Bass</strong> in the device chain, then <kbd
                    >Shift</kbd
                >-click the final <strong>Reverb</strong>
                to select the instrument and all downstream effects
            </li>
            <li>
                Right-click the selection → <strong>Group</strong> — Ableton wraps
                them in an <strong>Instrument Rack</strong>
            </li>
            <li>
                Click the rack title bar and rename it
                <code>Retrograde – Gothic</code>
            </li>
            <li>
                Right-click the rack title bar → <strong
                    >Save to User Library</strong
                > — saves under <em>Places → User Library</em>
                as a <code>.adg</code> preset; drag onto any new MIDI track to recall
                the complete Retrograde + processing chain instantly
            </li>
            <li>
                Note: the <code>Return — Bass Space</code> track is not stored in
                the rack — save the full Live Set as a template to keep the return
                routing intact
            </li>
        </ol>
    </article>
</MainLayout>
